# Codexify Slash Command + Obsidian Tool Spec v0.1

## 1. Purpose

Define a **single canonical command system** that powers:

1. Composer `/` palette

2. Internal CLI (`codexify ...`)

3. Guardian action invocation

And introduce **Obsidian as a first-class tool surface** with:

- read (retrieval)

- control (commands)

- maintenance (lint / health)

---

# 2. Core Principle

> One command registry → many surfaces

No duplication.

```ts
CommandRegistry → {
  CLI
  Slash UI
  Guardian invocation
}
```

---

# 3. Command Contract (Canonical)

This is the core shape every command must conform to.

```ts
type Command = {
  id: string            // "obsidian.ingest"
  namespace: string     // "obsidian"
  name: string          // "ingest"

  description: string
  aliases?: string[]

  category: 
    | "thread"
    | "doc"
    | "project"
    | "workspace"
    | "profile"
    | "flow"
    | "secure"
    | "connect"
    | "obsidian"

  args: CommandArg[]

  permissions: {
    requiresAuth: boolean
    requiresProject?: boolean
    filesystem?: "none" | "scoped" | "full"
  }

  execution: {
    mode: "sync" | "async"
    handler: string        // command bus handler id
  }

  preview?: {
    available: boolean
    description?: string
  }
}
```

---

# 4. Execution Flow

All commands go through the same pipeline:

```text
Composer / CLI / Guardian
        ↓
Command Bus
        ↓
Validation (args + permissions)
        ↓
Command Run (persisted)
        ↓
Execution Handler
        ↓
Command Events (streamed)
        ↓
Result → Chat / UI / Flow
```

This already aligns with your system:

- command runs

- event stream

- deterministic execution layer

---

# 5. Slash Command UX Contract

When user types `/`:

### UI must provide

- fuzzy search

- aliases

- short description

- argument hints

- permission badges

- preview/dry-run indicator

### Example

```id="cmd_ui_example"
/obsidian ingest
→ Ingest new raw files into your vault

/obsidian find "context broker"
→ Search compiled wiki

/secure lock
→ Lock encrypted vault
```

---

# 6. Obsidian Tool Definition

## Identity

```ts
Tool: Obsidian
Type: Local Knowledge Substrate
Mode: Read + Compile + Maintain
```

## Responsibilities

|Capability|Description|
|---|---|
|ingest|process `/raw` into structured wiki|
|compile|build / update knowledge graph|
|lint|detect gaps, inconsistencies|
|query|serve structured knowledge|
|link|maintain relationships|

This directly mirrors Karpathy’s pattern:

- ingest → compile → maintain → query ([techbuddies.io](https://www.techbuddies.io/2026/04/04/inside-karpathys-llm-knowledge-base-a-markdown-first-alternative-to-rag-for-autonomous-archives/?utm_source=chatgpt.com "Inside Karpathy’s LLM Knowledge Base: A Markdown-First Alternative to RAG for Autonomous Archives - techbuddies.io"))

---

# 7. Obsidian Command Set (v0.1)

## 7.1 Ingest

```ts
id: "obsidian.ingest"
```

### Behavior

- scans `/raw`

- processes new files

- updates wiki

### Args

```ts
{
  path?: string
  force?: boolean
}
```

---

## 7.2 Status

```ts
id: "obsidian.status"
```

### Returns

- number of notes

- last ingest time

- health status

- orphan nodes

---

## 7.3 Find

```ts
id: "obsidian.find"
```

### Args

```ts
{
  query: string
}
```

### Behavior

- navigates compiled wiki

- returns:

  - relevant notes

  - linked concepts

---

## 7.4 Lint (critical)

```ts
id: "obsidian.lint"
```

### Behavior

- detect:

  - unlinked notes

  - missing backlinks

  - contradictions

  - stale summaries

This is what turns the system into a **living archive**.

---

## 7.5 Summarize

```ts
id: "obsidian.summarize"
```

### Args

```ts
{
  topic: string
}
```

### Behavior

- reads multiple wiki nodes

- synthesizes answer

---

## 7.6 Refresh

```ts
id: "obsidian.refresh"
```

### Behavior

- recompile selected nodes

- update relationships

---

# 8. Retrieval Integration (critical boundary)

## Source Selector

```ts
source_mode:
  - project
  - personal_knowledge
  - obsidian   // new
```

### Behavior

When `obsidian` selected:

```text
1. Query wiki index
2. Traverse linked notes
3. Assemble context
4. Pass to LLM
```

---

## Retrieval Precedence (v0.1)

```text
IF source == obsidian:
    use wiki first
    fallback → project RAG

IF source == personal_knowledge:
    use RAG first
    optional → wiki enrichment
```

---

# 9. Dual Memory Model (explicit)

Codexify now has:

## A. Retrieval Memory (RAG)

- raw docs

- embeddings

- broad recall

## B. Compiled Memory (Obsidian)

- structured markdown

- linked concepts

- accumulated knowledge

Karpathy’s model replaces repeated recomputation with:

> “compile once, reuse forever” ([Agent Wars](https://agent-wars.com/news/2025-01-15-karpathy-llm-wiki-persistent-knowledge-base?utm_source=chatgpt.com "Karpathy's LLM Wiki Pattern: Compile Knowledge Once, Query Forever — Agent Wars"))

Codexify should **not replace RAG**  
It should **layer on top of it**

---

# 10. Guardrails

## DO NOT

- treat Obsidian as writable from chat (yet)

- claim live sync

- collapse command + retrieval layers

- expose raw filesystem mutation without permissions

## MUST

- keep Obsidian read-only in retrieval

- keep ingest behind commands

- preserve audit trail (command runs)

---

# 11. Future Extensions (not v0.1)

- `/obsidian.suggest-save`

- `/obsidian.auto-link`

- `/obsidian.graph-view`

- flow integration:

  - `/flow create from obsidian`

---

# 12. System Summary (compressed)

```text
Slash Commands → Control plane
Source Selector → Data plane

Obsidian:
  - controlled via commands
  - read via retrieval

Guardian:
  - executes commands
  - queries knowledge
  - bridges both
```

---

# Final Read

You now have:

- a **shell (commands)**

- a **memory system (wiki + RAG)**

- a **runtime (Guardian)**

That combination is rare.

Most systems pick one.

You’re wiring all three together.

---

If you want next, we should define:

> **exact retrieval arbitration logic**  
> (when Guardian chooses Obsidian vs RAG vs external tools)

That’s where this stops being “cool” and becomes **predictable and reliable**.
